When a user selects multiple images from a file input, the images are usually displayed in the order they were selected. However, there is no built-in way to access the order of the selected images programmatically.

One approach to figuring out the order of the images would be to assign each selected image a unique identifier (such as a timestamp) and store it in an array in the order they were selected. Here's an example of how this can be done using JavaScript:
```html
<input type="file" id="image-input" multiple>

<script>
const input = document.getElementById('image-input');
let images = [];

input.addEventListener('change', function(event) {
  const files = event.target.files;
  for (let i = 0; i < files.length; i++) {
    const file = files[i];
    const timestamp = Date.now();
    images.push({id: timestamp, file: file});
  }

  // sort the array based on the unique identifier
  images.sort((a, b) => a.id - b.id);

  // now the images array contains the selected images in the order they were selected
  console.log(images);
});
</script>
```
In this example, we listen for the `change` event on the file input and loop through the selected files to assign each image a unique identifier (a timestamp in this case) and push it to the `images` array. We then sort the array based on the unique identifier to get the images in the order they were selected. The `images` array can then be used to display the images or perform any other operations that require them in order.

